## Text Generation Rules

Follow these whenever you generate text for UI or developer surfaces.

### A. Placeholders and helper text
- Be informative, not decorative. State what to enter and why it matters.
- Keep ≤ 12 words when possible; sentence case; no trailing period.
- Avoid "e.g."; prefer "For example: …" sparingly. Use concrete examples.
- Avoid jargon; if a term is necessary (DP-1, FF1), assume minimal context.
- Accessibility: avoid emoji-only cues; be screen-reader friendly.

Good:
```
Wallet address (0x…) required to link your collection
Add a title to help you find this playlist later
Search artists, works, or collections
```

Bad:
```
Type here…
Enter value
Awesome title!!!
```

### B. Error messages and empty states
- Lead with the problem, follow with one actionable next step.
- Own the issue with "We" when system-caused; avoid blaming the user.
- Include scope/context (what failed), keep it under ~2 short sentences.
- Provide a recovery action: retry, check connection, contact support, or offline fallback.
- Never leak stack traces, IDs, or sensitive data. No "Oops". No exclamation spam.
- Prefer sentence case; one exclamation max, rarely necessary.

Good:
```
We couldn't load your collection. Check your connection, then Retry.
Linking failed due to a timeout. Try again or use manual code linking.
This channel is empty. Add works to see them here.
```

Bad:
```
Error 500: server exploded!!!
You did something wrong.
Oops, something went wrong.
```

### C. Notifications and toasts
- Past-tense for completed actions; present-progress for ongoing.
- One idea per toast; include a link/button if an action is expected.
- Keep the sentence concise; avoid filler like "just" or "really".

Example:
```
Playlist saved. View
Sync in progress…
```

### D. Commit messages and PR descriptions
- Commit title: imperative, ≤ 72 chars; body explains why and impact.
- Reference user outcome and any trade-offs; link issues when relevant.

### E. Docs and changelogs
- Start with what changed and why it matters; list concise steps/impacts.
- Use bullets; avoid long paragraphs. Prefer examples over theory.

### F. Formatting and style conventions
- Sentence case; avoid title case in UI strings.
- Labels/tooltips: no trailing period. Full sentences in descriptions may use periods.
- Numerals: prefer digits (e.g., "2 playlists"). Units explicit.
- Dates/times: ISO or localized by platform; avoid ambiguous formats.
- Use consistent terminology: FF1, DP-1, playlist, channel, work, collection.

### G. Internationalization
- Keep strings standalone and translatable; avoid hard-coded concatenation.
- Provide placeholders with clear semantics (e.g., {workCount}).
- Avoid culturally loaded idioms. Keep punctuation simple.

## Quick checklist (before shipping text)
- Does it state the why or next step?
- Is it concise, human, and free of jargon?
- Does it respect privacy and avoid leakage?
- Is there a clear recovery or action?
- Will it translate well and read accessibly?

## Voice examples (quick reference)
Good, on-brand:
```
This update keeps playlists playable on FF1 even when offline.
We found a sync gap with channels; retrying won't duplicate works.
```
Crisp experiment note:
```
Prototype cuts render time ~20%. Trade-off: higher memory use on older FF1.
Next: try streaming decode to balance both.
```
Warm, human:
```
Pairing took longer than expected. We've simplified the flow—tell us where it still drags.
```
